<Author>kebdc
<Content>The Ritz Rocks We just returned from an amazing three-night stay at the Ritz San Juan (March 1-4). Upon check-in we were offered a choice of the standard room we had originally booked - with two doubles and a view, or a club-level room with no view (well of the very nearby airport and mountains) and a king-size bed - at the same rate. We chose the club-level room and we were glad we did! The club was just down the hall from our room and seemed to always be open for a different meal or cocktail or snack. Each day there were four services: a continental breakfast, lunch, cocktails and hors d'oeuvres, and desserts and cordials. The meals were buffet style and were light, healthy and delicious. It doesn't get much better than your boyfriend handing you a glass of champagne during your shower because there were two chilled uncorked bottles at all times in the club room down the hall. The club staff members were very friendly and helpful. The club room had a beautiful view of the pool and ocean and there is a balcony with seating if you want to have your meal outside (this more than made up for the airport view). There are also books, iPods, and a computer for your use. Considering the price of the meals in the hotel - according to other reviewers -(we wouldn't know because we never had to pay for any of them) and the price of drinks - Club Level is the way to go if it's an option for you. We checked-in late - around midnight - so maybe that had something to do with our luck. Our room was beautiful and roomy and room service was impeccable. A fresh orchid along with chocolates and fresh bottles of water were bedside each day. Plenty of fresh new towels in the bathroom - along with robes and slippers. Other reviewers complained about the water pressure but I thought it was fine. If you want lots of water pressure go stand under one of the lion spouts in the pool!The hotel is lively - yet quiet and elegant at the same time. One night there was a live bongo performance in the lobby that was fun to see - but for the most part it was quiet. We were fortunate to have beautiful weather each day - around 85 and sunny and breezy. The ocean water was very warm and the sand was soft and clean. We never had to wait for chairs or towels at the beach - although chairs by the pool were a little difficult to negotiate.If you know how to sail, then definitely take adavantage of the catamarans available - and included in the resort fee. Fortunately my bf is an expert sailor and handled our boat effortlessly - however we saw a couple of peeps have difficulty turning their boat around and coming dangerously close to drifting upon the sharp coral that is just below the water surface in some areas. Ouch!As far as other activities at the hotel - the spinning classes run by Francisco were challenging (I'm told) - although I would pass on the beginning yoga class (Jackie) - unless you have never taken a yoga class before. It was basically 45 minutes divided into 10 minutes of light stretching, 20 minutes of ab work, then 15 minutes of lying on your mat (I guess that was supposed to be shivasina). I heard Francisco has a fantastic hatha class, but I opted to sleep-in instead.I highly recommend Evelyn if you are going to have a massage treatment at the spa. I chose the 50 minute deep tissue and she was excellent. It was a perfect massage experience. The padding on the table is heated and feels amazing. They also use heated and scented towels and pillows on your eyes, legs, and under knees - usually considered signature treatment at other spas.The casino is super-fun, although a little more low-key than the one at the Hotel El San Juan which was absolutely packed. At least at the Ritz you never had to wait for a spot at the table and you didn't feel like a loser for making $2 bets on roulette! The other casino was a little more intimidating in my opinion. At the Ritz If you get a players card, then make sure the dealers know you have it and give you credit accurately for your time and average bets.The dealers were very friendly - although it took a little while to get a cocktail. The pool area at night is beautiful. The lights, palm trees, pool, fountains, flowers and warm breezes are amazing. You can hear the coqui frogs - although I'm told they are not really frogs - throughout the grounds. They sound like chirping birds. I was also told their little chirp means I love you, but maybe they just say that to woo tourists.Old San Juan is beautiful both day and night. During the day check out the grounds of the Fort El Morro and Fort San Cristobal. In town there are many shops, restaurants, and art galleries. Also - outlet shopping including Coach, Polo, Dooney and Burke - and a few others I can't remember.For our one night in Old San Juan we had dinner at Barrachina. It seemed a little touristy but we decided to stay for dinner for the hour-long flamenco show. The food was ok, but the show was fabulous. Not only was there a spanish guitarist, but also a singer - in addition to the three flamenco dancers. Service was a little on the slow side but the drinks were stiff. If you go there make sure you keep your receipt. We were half-way across Old San Juan after dinner in an alley on our way to the New Yorican, when one of the waiters from Barrachina tracked us down saying we didn't pay! After producing our receipt the thankful waiter returned to the restaurant - but it could have been a not so pleasant situation. After dinner we went to Marmalade for a digestif. Marmalade is a jolt of contemporary and chic compared with the more romantic Spanish atmosphere of Barrachina that included candles, wrought iron and other Spanish decor.If you are in Old San Juan and need taxi service back to the Ritz, then call Ana Figueroa with Island Taxi Service (787-450-3242). She is a taxi driver/ tour guide and is super -fun and hilarious (and informative). We laughed with her the entire cab ride back to the hotel.We spent one night hanging out at the Hotel El San Juan. I mentioned their casino above...They also have a few restaurants - including The Palm - where we had dinner - and a nightclub and an additional live music lounge with dancing if you are in the mood. I had probably the best mojito I have ever tasted at the bar along the wall next to the tobacco shop.It was a fabulous trip. The Ritz was amazing. I would go back in a heartbeat!One last tip though would be to carry-on your luggage if possible. The SJ airport was nuts on the way out and United still doesn't know where my suitcase is. But the direct flight home cannot be beat. 
